<span class="displaytext"><b>"[gov. (candidate last)] lambasted (PARTY NAME) health care plans as 'knee-jerk, single-payer' policies run by the federal government. he said (PARTY NAME)s should fight back with 'free market' proposals. his own plan is a blend of tax incentives, creative financing to help the uninsured without raising taxes or federal spending, and a state-based system that would depend on governors to fix the country's health-care problems." (steven thomma, "(candidate last)'s health care fix," <em>mcclatchy newspapers</em>, 8/24/07)</b> <p align="center"> <b>the (candidate last) vision: market-based health care reform</b> </p><p><b> <u>gov. (candidate last) supports using the states as laboratories of innovation:</u> </b> </p><p><b>gov. (candidate last)'s plan emphasizes individual state-by-state health care reform, not universal health care.</b> "governor (candidate last)'s health care reform plan is a comprehensive solution to america's health care ills that expands access to affordable, portable, quality, private health insurance. but rather than relying on a one-size-fits-all, government-run system, governor (candidate last)'s plan recognizes the importance of the role of the states in leading reform and the need for innovation in dealing with rising health care costs and the problem of the uninsured." ((candidate last) for president, "expanding access to affordable health care," press release, 8/24/07) </p><p><b>gov. (candidate last) believes that a "one-size-fits-all" approach to health care reform is wrong.</b> "but [gov. (candidate last)] will also aim to reassure conservatives by saying that a 'one size fits all' solution isn't right for the 50 states. as for why he would use a different philosophy as president than as governor, they say he would have greater powers in the white house. 'massachusetts didn't have the federal tax code to play with,' said glenn hubbard, a former bush administration chief economist, now advising the (candidate last) campaign." (mary jacoby and sarah lueck, "(candidate last)'s federal prescription," <em>the wall street journal</em>, 8/24/07) </p><p><b>gov. (candidate last) does not believe in government mandates for health insurance.</b> "in a speech before the florida medical association in hollywood, fla., mr. (candidate last) will present a program that won't include new government mandates for individuals or companies to buy coverage, policies long considered anathema by many conservatives - and that were features of the program enacted in massachusetts." (mary jacoby and sarah lueck, "(candidate last)'s federal prescription," <em>the wall street journal</em>, 8/24/07) </p><p>- <b>gov. (candidate last): "we'll get all the way there, but it's not through a mandate ... if some states were going to drag their heels, i'm not going to have the federal government step in."</b> (steven thomma, "(candidate last)'s health care fix," <em>mcclatchy newspapers</em>, 8/24/07) </p><p><b> <u>gov. (candidate last) supports conservative, market-based heath care reform:</u> </b> </p><p><b>gov. (candidate last)'s plan will decrease costs by expanding the growth of the private health insurance market.</b> "governor (candidate last) believes that by expanding and deregulating the private health insurance market, we can decrease costs and ensure that more americans have access to affordable, portable, quality, private health insurance." ((candidate last) for president, "expanding access to affordable health care," press release, 8/24/07) </p><p><b>gov. (candidate last) focuses on using tax breaks to decrease health care costs.</b> "instead, mr. (candidate last) plans to focus on tax breaks and streamlining regulations, policies his advisers say would essentially create a new, freer market for health insurance, driving down costs and providing incentives for individuals to buy their own plans. it is an approach president bush and many (PARTY NAME) economists have embraced." (mary jacoby and sarah lueck, "(candidate last)'s federal prescription," <em>the wall street journal</em>, 8/24/07) </p><p><b>- gov. (candidate last): "the market can work to solve our health care needs, and that's the great, exciting news."</b> (msnbc, (PARTY NAME) presidential candidate debate, simi valley, ca, 5/3/07) </p><p><b> <u>gov. (candidate last) successfully passed health care reform legislation in massachusetts:</u> </b> </p><p><b>gov. (candidate last)'s success passing health care reform in massachusetts sets an example for other states.</b> "as governor of massachusetts, governor (candidate last) successfully led the effort for comprehensive health care reform, and he recognizes that the federal government must do what it can to facilitate effective change at the state level. his reforms will give states greater flexibility. but governor (candidate last)'s conservative reforms also make the states true partners in the effort to expand access to affordable, quality health insurance." ((candidate last) for president, "expanding access to affordable health care," press release, 8/24/07) </p><p><b>gov. (candidate last) worked with (PARTY NAME)s and (PARTY NAME) to pass health care reform in massachusetts.</b> gov. (candidate last): "i'm delighted with the fact that we in our state worked together across the aisle, (PARTY NAME)s and (PARTY NAME), to find a way to get health care for all of our citizens that's affordable and that's portable. ... the heritage foundation worked on it with us. we had people on both sides of the aisle." (msnbc, (PARTY NAME) presidential candidate debate, simi valley, ca, 5/3/07) </p><p><b>- massachusetts (PARTY NAME)s and (PARTY NAME) passed health care reform 191-2.</b> "lawmakers overwhelmingly approved the bill tuesday. the plan hailed as a national model would dramatically expand access to health care over the next three years. ... the house approved the bill on a 154-2 vote. the senate endorsed it 37-0." (steve leblanc, "(candidate last) set to sign bill to require health insurance for all," <em>the associated press</em>, 4/5/06) </p><p></p><p align="center"> <b>sen. (candidate full): "i want to have universal health care."</b> <br/> </p><p><br/> <b> <u>sen. (candidate full) is pushing big government-run "universal health care":</u> </b> </p><p><b>sen. (candidate last): "i've set big goals for my presidency. i want to have universal health care ..."</b> (abc, (PARTY NAME) presidential debate, des moines, ia, 8/19/07) </p><p><b>sen. (candidate last) said passing government-run universal health care will be one of her top priorities as president.</b> sen. (candidate full): "passage of a universal health coverage plan will be one of my top priorities as president. it is time for bold yet practical solutions and i will use today's encouraging news to continue my efforts to build support for universal health care." (hillary for president, "statement of (candidate full) on announcement of the 'better health care together' campaign," press release, 2/7/07) </p><p><b>sen. (candidate last) wants to make government-run universal health care "an american value."</b> sen. (candidate last): "but more important, we have to have a sense of national commitment that universal health care is an american value." (cnn/youtube, (PARTY NAME) presidential candidate debate, charleston, sc, 7/23/07) </p><p><b> <u>sen. (candidate last) will unveil her plan for government-run universal health care in the fall:</u> </b> </p><p><b>sen. (candidate last) "will outline her plan for universal health care coverage next month."</b> "(PARTY NAME) presidential hopeful hillary rodham (candidate last) rolled out the second stage of her health care policy thursday, promising to improve quality by raising standards for providers, educating patients and requiring insurers to reward innovation ... she started with a speech in june on reducing costs, followed by thursday's address on quality, and will outline her plan for universal health care c